---

<ModuleLayout module={module} panelMode={true} tracks={tracks}>

  <!-- Module intro — matches ModuleBridge style used in M2+ -->
  <div class="mb-8 p-5 rounded-xl bg-navy/5 border border-navy/10">
    <p class="text-sm text-navy font-heading mb-2">
      <strong>RG Foundations</strong> — What "responsible gambling" actually means, the informed choice model behind Playbook, and the two-tier content system.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-navy mb-3 font-heading"><strong>By the end of this module, you will be able to:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-sm text-n700 mb-4 space-y-1.5 pl-4 list-disc">
      <li>Explain the three-layer RG framework (Compliance, Public Health, Informed Choice)</li>
      <li>Describe the Information Gap and why it matters for player education</li>
      <li>Apply the two-tier content model to classify any piece of player-facing content</li>
    </ul>
    <button
      id="start-narration-btn"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 bg-teal text-navy font-heading font-bold rounded-lg hover:bg-teal-light transition-colors text-sm"
    >
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M8 5v14l11-7z"/></svg>
      Play Audio Guide
    </button>
  </div>

  <script>
    document.getElementById('start-narration-btn')?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('start-playback'));
    });
  </script>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 1.1: What does RG actually mean?        -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="what-does-rg-mean" data-slide-index="0" data-lesson-slug="what-does-rg-mean" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>What does RG actually mean?</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      "Responsible gambling" is one of the most used phrases in the industry. It's also one of the least useful. Everyone says it. Few define it. Let's fix that.
    </p>

    <p>
      Ask ten people what it means and you'll get ten different answers — depending on whether they're a player, a regulator, an operator, or a researcher. That ambiguity isn't harmless. When a phrase means everything, it means nothing. And when your foundational concept means nothing, everything built on top of it is shaky.
    </p>

    <p>
      So let's nail it down. At its core, responsible gambling is about one thing:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p><strong>Helping players manage how they spend their time and money on gambling.</strong></p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      That's the through-line. Every compliance framework, every helpline number, every piece of educational content, every tool — they all exist to serve that single goal. But different stakeholders come at it from very different angles. Understanding those angles is what separates surface-level <Glossary term="RG" definition="Responsible Gambling — the broad term for industry practices that help players manage their time and money" /> knowledge from the kind that actually shapes content decisions.
    </p>

    <h3 id="three-perspectives-one-goal">Three perspectives, one goal</h3>

    <p id="the-public-perspective-awareness-and-accountability" class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">The public perspective: awareness and accountability</p>
    <p>
      For the general public and advocacy groups, RG means the industry takes genuine responsibility for the product it sells. Gambling companies shouldn't just profit from entertainment — they should make sure people understand what they're buying. The public expects <strong>transparency</strong> (what are the real odds?), <strong>accessible support</strong> (not a helpline number buried in a footer), and <strong>genuine effort</strong> — not a checkbox exercise.
    </p>

    <p>
      This perspective matters because it shapes reputation. An operator that treats RG as a compliance cost will eventually face a trust problem — with regulators, with media, and with the players who notice the gap between marketing promises and educational reality.
    </p>

    <p id="the-regulator-perspective-standards-and-compliance" class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">The regulator perspective: standards and compliance</p>
    <p>
      For regulators, RG means <strong>enforceable standards</strong>. Helpline numbers displayed correctly. Self-exclusion flows that work. Advertising that doesn't target vulnerable populations. Age verification. Mandatory messaging. Compliance is the <strong>floor</strong> — the minimum every operator must meet, regardless of their broader approach to player education.
    </p>

    <p id="the-consumer-perspective-informed-choice" class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">The consumer perspective: informed choice</p>
    <p>
      For the player, RG means having the <strong>information and tools</strong> to make good decisions. It means understanding the odds before you bet, knowing how long you've been playing, and being able to set limits that actually work. Players don't want to be lectured. They don't want to be treated as patients. They want to be <strong>equipped</strong>. This is where Playbook lives — giving players the information they need to make their own choices well.
    </p>

    <p>
      Think about it from the player's seat: you chose to spend your entertainment budget on gambling. You're a competent adult who made a deliberate choice. What you need isn't a warning — it's useful information. How does the house edge affect your bankroll over time? What does a 40x wagering requirement actually cost? How do parlay odds compound? Playbook provides that information.
    </p>

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>RG means helping players manage their time and money. Three stakeholders see this differently — public (accountability), regulators (standards), consumers (informed choice) — and Playbook serves all three by empowering the consumer with the information they need.</p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 1.1b: The Engagement Gap                -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="the-engagement-gap" data-slide-index="0" data-lesson-slug="what-does-rg-mean" data-has-exercise class="module-section py-16">
    <h3 id="the-engagement-gap-heading">The Engagement Gap</h3>

    <p>
      Every major gambling operator invests heavily in commercial content. Sleek apps. Polished advertising. Generous bonuses designed by entire teams of marketers, designers, and copywriters. World-class creative.
    </p>

    <p>
      And their player education content? A wall of text buried in the footer. Written by compliance. Designed by nobody. Read by no one.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="The Engagement Gap">
      <p>The engagement gap is the difference between the quality of an operator's commercial content and the quality of their player education content. For most operators, it's enormous — and players notice instantly.</p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <p>
      This gap often exists because player education has been treated as a <strong>compliance problem</strong>, not a <strong>marketing communications challenge</strong>. It typically lives outside marketing — owned by legal, compliance, or external program providers. Those teams ensure requirements are met. But they're not resourced to build brands, write copy that people want to read, or create campaigns players actually interact with.
    </p>

    <p>
      The result: content that satisfies the regulator but fails the player. A tiny helpline number in 10px gray text. A "Play Responsibly" tagline that nobody has ever read and thought, <em>I should pay attention to this.</em> A self-exclusion option buried four clicks deep in account settings.
    </p>

    <p>
      The content is present. It is also functionally invisible.
    </p>

    <h3 id="playbooks-thesis">Playbook's thesis</h3>

    <blockquote>
      <p><strong>Player education is a marketing communications challenge, not a compliance requirement.</strong></p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      If you treat player education with the same creative investment, brand thinking, and production quality as commercial content, players will engage with it to the same level as all marketing communications. Not because they're forced to, but because it's genuinely worth their time.
    </p>

    <p>
      Playbook is the tool that makes this possible — an open-source brand system any operator can adopt, adapt, and deploy under their own brand to close the engagement gap.
    </p>

    <SpotTheGap client:visible />
    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>RG means helping players manage their time and money. Three stakeholders see this differently — public (accountability), consumers (informed choice), regulators (standards). The engagement gap between commercial content quality and education content quality is the specific problem Playbook exists to solve.</p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 2: The Information Gap                   -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="informed-choice-model" data-slide-index="1" data-lesson-slug="informed-choice-model" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>The Information Gap</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      Most operators give players rules. Very few give them understanding. The gap between what operators know about their products and what players know is where problems develop — and where Playbook does its work.
    </p>

    <h3 id="gambling-is-a-complicated-product">Gambling is a complicated product</h3>

    <p>
      Think about what a player actually faces. Every gambling product involves <strong>probability, expected value, house edge, variance, and game-specific mechanics</strong>. None of this is intuitive.
    </p>

    <p>
      A -110 betting line. A 35:1 roulette payout. A 96% <Glossary term="RTP" definition="Return to Player — the theoretical percentage of wagered money a game pays back over time" /> on a slot machine. These numbers carry real financial meaning — but most players can't decode them without help. Not because players are foolish. Because gambling products are genuinely complex, and the information needed to understand them hasn't been made accessible.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Information Asymmetry">
      <p>Operators understand the math behind their products deeply — their business model depends on it. Players generally don't. This Information Gap means players can't make fully informed choices, and that means that players are less likely to play and more likely to put themselves at risk. Reducing that gap is Playbook's core job — and the reason this entire framework exists.</p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <p>
      When people face complex decisions without adequate information, they make worse choices. This is true for financial products, healthcare, insurance — and gambling. The solution isn't to prevent people from making choices. It's to <strong>close the Information Gap</strong> so they can choose well.
    </p>

    <h3 id="what-players-actually-need">What players actually need</h3>

    <p>
      The informed choice model says players need three things to make good decisions:
    </p>

    <div class="list-card">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>How to play</strong> — the rules, the mechanics, the basics of the game</li>
        <li><strong>How the game works</strong> — the math behind it: house edge, odds, <Glossary term="RNG" definition="Random Number Generator — the algorithm that determines outcomes in digital gambling games, ensuring each result is independent" />, expected value, variance</li>
        <li><strong>Where risks exist</strong> — what can go wrong, and how tools and features can help manage it</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>
      Most operators cover the first one. Some attempt the second. Almost nobody does the third well. And the gap between what operators know and what players know is where problems develop.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── SUB-SECTION: Four Premises ─── -->
  <section id="four-premises" data-slide-index="1" data-lesson-slug="informed-choice-model" class="module-section py-16">
    <h3 id="people-make-better-decisions-when-they-can-do-so-rationally">People make better decisions when they can do so rationally</h3>

    <p>
      This is the core premise. Not complicated. Not controversial. Just true.
    </p>

    <p>
      When players have accurate information about how games work, what the odds mean, and what tools are available to manage their play — the vast majority make sound decisions. They set budgets. They play within their means. They walk away when they're done.
    </p>

    <p>
      The informed choice framework rests on four premises:
    </p>

    <div class="list-card">
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Most people who gamble do so without problems.</strong> The vast majority of players gamble recreationally, within their means, and without developing difficulties. This is the norm, not the exception. Content should be designed for them — the majority — not exclusively for a small percentage who develop difficulties.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Gambling is entertainment.</strong> It's a leisure activity with a cost — the house edge. Understanding that cost doesn't ruin the experience. It makes it more informed. Like knowing the price of a movie ticket before you buy it. (Note: advertised house edge figures like blackjack's ~0.5% assume optimal play strategy — most players face a higher effective edge.)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Difficulties arise from lack of information and lack of control — not from the activity itself.</strong> When players understand how games work and have tools to manage their play, the vast majority make sound decisions.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Responsibility is shared across multiple stakeholders.</strong> Players make their own choices — and that autonomy matters. Operators provide accurate information and effective tools. Regulators set standards. Support services exist for those who need them. No single party bears the entire burden.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h3 id="where-the-model-comes-from">Where the model comes from</h3>

    <p>
      The informed choice framework isn't an invention of the gambling industry. It draws on established ideas from three fields:
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Intellectual Foundations">
      <p><strong>Consumer psychology</strong> — decades of research shows that people make better purchasing decisions when product information is comprehensible, accessible, and honest. Gambling is no different: give players clear information about how a product works, and most will self-regulate.</p>
      <p><strong>Economic adverse selection</strong> — when one party in a transaction knows far more than the other (operators understand probability, variance, and house edge; most players don't), the Information Gap leads to poor outcomes. Closing that gap is a market-efficiency argument, not a moral one.</p>
      <p><strong>Liberal ethics</strong> — the model sits at the intersection of personal liberty and duty of care. Pure paternalism ("protect players from themselves") removes autonomy. Pure laissez-faire ("they chose to play") ignores the Information Gap. Informed choice is the middle path: equip people to make their own decisions, then respect those decisions.</p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <p>
      This theoretical grounding is what separates Playbook from generic responsible gambling content. Playbook isn't "be careful" messaging — it's a structured approach to closing the information asymmetry between operators and players, rooted in how people actually make decisions.
    </p>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── SUB-SECTION: Three Complementary Layers ─── -->
  <section id="three-layers-not-three-alternatives" data-slide-index="1" data-lesson-slug="informed-choice-model" data-has-exercise class="module-section py-16">
    <h3>Three layers, not three alternatives</h3>

    <p>
      The industry often presents RG approaches as competing models. You're either a <em>compliance</em> shop, or a <em>public health</em> advocate, or an <em>informed choice</em> operator. Pick one.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is wrong. They're <strong>complementary layers</strong>, and an operator needs all three:
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-6">
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-n300/30 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
        <span class="inline-block text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-n500 bg-n100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded mb-3">Layer 1</span>
        <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mb-2">Compliance</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n500 font-semibold mb-1">Gambling industry</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 mb-2"><strong>Driven by:</strong> Regulators, Legislators</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700">Helpline display, age verification, self-exclusion, mandatory messaging</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-info/30 bg-info/5 p-5 shadow-sm">
        <span class="inline-block text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-info bg-info/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded mb-3">Layer 2</span>
        <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mb-2">Public Health</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n500 font-semibold mb-1">Population outcomes</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 mb-2"><strong>Driven by:</strong> Regulators, public institutions</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700">Prevalence research, advertising restrictions, treatment funding, harm monitoring</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-teal/30 bg-teal/5 p-5 shadow-sm">
        <span class="inline-block text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-teal-dark bg-teal/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded mb-3">Layer 3</span>
        <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mb-2">Informed Choice</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n500 font-semibold mb-1">Consumer content</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 mb-2"><strong>Driven by:</strong> Operators</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700">Odds education, tools-as-features, myth-busting, game guides, Playbook</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      <strong>Compliance is non-negotiable.</strong> It's the floor. Every operator meets it, regardless of strategy.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Public health concerns inform how you operate.</strong> Population-level research, advertising standards, prevalence monitoring — these shape the regulatory environment and set the context for everything else.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Informed choice is where Playbook lives.</strong> It's the content strategy that empowers individual players to manage their time and money — through education, tools, and content that's actually worth engaging with.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Three Layers Working Together">
      <p>Compliance sets the floor. Public health shapes the environment. Informed choice empowers the individual. Playbook operates at the informed choice layer — but all three layers are essential and complementary, not competing alternatives.</p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <p>
      Playbook doesn't replace compliance or dismiss public health. It operates at the informed choice layer while respecting the others. When you deploy Playbook, your compliance requirements are still met. The difference is that the content <em>around</em> those requirements is now worth reading.
    </p>

    <ThreeLayerDiagram client:visible />

    <LayerClassifier client:visible />
    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>Gambling is a complicated product with an Information Gap between operators and players. The informed choice approach closes that gap by giving players what they need: how to play, how the game works, and where risks exist. Compliance, Public Health, and Informed Choice are complementary layers — not competing alternatives. Playbook operates at the Informed Choice layer.</p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 3: The Two-Tier System                  -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="two-tier-system" data-slide-index="2" data-lesson-slug="two-tier-system" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>The Two-Tier Playbook System</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      The informed choice model makes a critical assumption: that players are making rational decisions. For the vast majority, that holds. But not always.
    </p>

    <h3 id="when-informed-choice-isnt-enough">When informed choice isn't enough</h3>

    <p>
      About 5% of Playbook content and engagement will be related to Support & Crisis situations. Some players gamble <strong>in ways that suggest difficulty</strong> — not because they lack information, but because impulse, habit, or loss of control overrides their ability to act on what they know.
    </p>

    <p>
      A player who understands house edge intellectually may still chase losses when emotions take over. A player who set a deposit limit last week may override it this week in a moment of frustration. Information alone doesn't fix this. It's a fundamentally different problem.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="The 95/5 Split" icon="alert-circle">
      <p><strong>~5%</strong> of Playbook content is allocated to Support & Crisis situations — addressing difficulty and loss of control rather than informed choice. Different problem, different response.</p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <p>
      You can't solve loss of control with a better odds explainer. A more detailed article about house edge won't help someone who can't stop even though they want to. These players need a different kind of response — <strong>immediate access to support, self-exclusion tools, and professional help</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is why Playbook operates on two tiers.
    </p>

    <h3 id="the-two-tiers">The two tiers</h3>

    <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-6">
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-teal/30 overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-teal/10 px-5 py-3 border-b border-teal/20">
          <TierBadge tier={1} />
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-lg mt-2">Entertainment Literacy</p>
        </div>
        <div class="divide-y divide-n100 bg-white">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2.5 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm"><span class="font-heading font-bold text-teal-dark">~95%</span><span class="text-n700">of content</span></div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700">Assumes rational decision-making with good information</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Goal:</strong> equip players with knowledge and tools</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Tone:</strong> confident, witty, informative</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Content:</strong> odds education, game guides, myth-busting, quizzes, tools-as-features</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700 italic">"Here's how the game actually works."</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-orange/30 overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-orange/10 px-5 py-3 border-b border-orange/20">
          <TierBadge tier={2} />
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-lg mt-2">Support & Crisis</p>
        </div>
        <div class="divide-y divide-n100 bg-white">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2.5 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm"><span class="font-heading font-bold text-orange-dark">~5%</span><span class="text-n700">of content</span></div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700">Addresses players in difficulty — loss of control, impulse, cognitive distortion</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Goal:</strong> connect to support with zero friction</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Tone:</strong> warm, direct, zero judgment</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Content:</strong> helplines, self-exclusion, cooling-off, crisis referrals</div>
          <div class="px-5 py-2.5 text-sm text-n700 italic">"We're here. No judgment. Here's help."</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── SUB-SECTION: Recognizing the Shift ─── -->
  <section id="recognizing-the-shift" data-slide-index="2" data-lesson-slug="two-tier-system" data-has-exercise class="module-section py-16">
    <h3>Recognizing the shift</h3>

    <p>
      How do you know when a player has moved from Tier 1 territory into Tier 2? You look for <strong>behavioral indicators</strong> — observable patterns that suggest a player's behavior may not align with their intentions:
    </p>

    <div class="grid gap-3 my-6">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 rounded-xl bg-white border border-n100 shadow-sm">
        <span class="shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-9 h-9 rounded-full bg-orange/10 flex items-center justify-center">
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-orange" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 7h8m0 0v8m0-8l-8 8-4-4-6 6" /></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Escalating deposits</strong> — spending more over time, especially after losses</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 rounded-xl bg-white border border-n100 shadow-sm">
        <span class="shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-9 h-9 rounded-full bg-orange/10 flex items-center justify-center">
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-orange" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M4 4v5h.582m15.356 2A8.001 8.001 0 004.582 9m0 0H9m11 11v-5h-.581m0 0a8.003 8.003 0 01-15.357-2m15.357 2H15" /></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Chasing losses</strong> — increasing bets to recover previous losses</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 rounded-xl bg-white border border-n100 shadow-sm">
        <span class="shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-9 h-9 rounded-full bg-orange/10 flex items-center justify-center">
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-orange" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" /></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Increasing session length and frequency</strong> — playing longer and more often</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 rounded-xl bg-white border border-n100 shadow-sm">
        <span class="shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-9 h-9 rounded-full bg-orange/10 flex items-center justify-center">
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-orange" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01m-6.938 4h13.856c1.54 0 2.502-1.667 1.732-2.5L13.732 4c-.77-.833-1.964-.833-2.732 0L4.082 16.5c-.77.833.192 2.5 1.732 2.5z" /></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Repeated limit increases</strong> — raising self-imposed limits shortly after hitting them</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 rounded-xl bg-white border border-n100 shadow-sm">
        <span class="shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-9 h-9 rounded-full bg-orange/10 flex items-center justify-center">
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-orange" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M21 21l-6-6m2-5a7 7 0 11-14 0 7 7 0 0114 0z" /></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="text-n700"><strong class="text-navy">Searching for support content</strong> — visiting helpline pages, searching "self-exclusion"</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy mt-4">
      As these signals get stronger, Tier 2 content should be prioritized for that player — surfaced more prominently, placed closer to the interaction, and always immediately accessible.
    </p>

    <p>
      Notice what's <em>not</em> on this list: clinical diagnostic criteria. You won't find <Glossary term="DSM" definition="Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders — the standard classification of mental disorders used by mental health professionals" /> checklists here. Players don't self-diagnose from clinical criteria, and operators aren't qualified to apply them. What works is <strong>behavioral description</strong> — language like "spending more than you planned" rather than "persistent and recurrent problematic gambling behavior."
    </p>

    <h3 id="why-the-955-split-matters">Why the 95/5 split matters</h3>

    <p>
      Most operators get this ratio backwards. They treat <em>all</em> player education as if it's crisis prevention — which makes it feel clinical, preachy, and irrelevant to the vast majority of players. The result: nobody reads any of it, including the people who need Tier 2 support the most.
    </p>

    <p>
      Playbook's approach: make Tier 1 content so genuinely engaging that players <em>choose</em> to interact with it. Then ensure Tier 2 support is always one tap away — accessible from any Tier 1 context, but never the dominant message.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>Think of it like a sports venue. The game, the atmosphere, the food — that's Tier 1. The first aid station and exit signs — that's Tier 2. Both are essential. Both save lives. But the venue is designed around the experience, not around the exits. And critically: <strong>the exits are always clearly marked.</strong></p>
    </blockquote>

    <h3 id="the-non-negotiable-rule">The non-negotiable rule</h3>

    <p>
      <strong>Tier 2 is always accessible.</strong> The helpline number, self-exclusion link, and support resources must be reachable from <em>every</em> Tier 1 context. A player reading a myth-busting article should be able to find support in one tap. But the article itself should never be framed as a warning or intervention.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the design principle that holds the two tiers together: engaging content for the majority, with immediate access to support for anyone who needs it, at any moment. No mixing. No compromise. Both, simultaneously.
    </p>

    <TierToggle client:visible />
    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>Tier 1 (95%) assumes rational decision-making and equips players with information and tools. Tier 2 (5%) exists because some gambling is driven by difficulty or loss of control — a different problem requiring a different response. Use behavioral indicators (not clinical criteria) to recognize the shift. And the non-negotiable: Tier 2 support is always one tap away from any Tier 1 context.</p>
    </KeyTakeaway>

    <GenerativeExercise
      client:visible
      title="Write a Tier 1 Deposit Limit Nudge"
      prompt="A player has just registered and is about to make their first deposit. Write a short Tier 1 message (3–4 sentences) that nudges them to set a deposit limit. Remember: Tier 1 is engaging, non-prescriptive, and treats limits as tools — not warnings."
      placeholder="Write your Tier 1 deposit-limit message here…"
      rubric={[
        'Uses language that frames limits as a tool, not a restriction',
        'Tone is conversational and Tier 1 — not clinical or warning-like',
        'Does not use stigmatizing language (no "problem," "responsible," "addiction")',
        'Includes a clear action — not just education',
      ]}
      modelAnswer="Setting a deposit limit is one of the smartest things you can do as a new player. It keeps your spending on your terms — think of it like a personal budget for entertainment. Most players who set limits say it actually makes the experience more enjoyable, not less. Tap below to choose the amount that works for you."
    />
  </section>

